						<summary>

						<p>On two stone slabs lying on the south side of the 2nd <hi rend="italic">prākāra</hi> Tuṟaikāṭṭumvaḷḷalār temple, Viḷanagar a hamlet of Arupādi.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Year 5: 976 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>It records an endowment of some pieces of land made after purchase by Ōraṭṭaṇaṉ Śōrabbaiyār, the chief queen <hi rend="italic">(agramahādēvi)</hi> of Uttamachōḷa, for offerings during the mid-night service in the temple of Tirunāḷarkōyil-Mahādēva at Viḷañagar, a <hi rend="italic">brahmadēya</hi> on the southern bank. These lands are stated to have been got freed from taxes <hi rend="italic">ūrkkīḻ-iṟaiyili</hi> by the <hi rend="italic">peruṅguri-sabhā</hi> of the place. The accountant of the <hi rend="italic">ūr</hi> Viḷainagar-uḍaiyāṉ and others figure as signatories.</p>						

						<p>Published in <hi rend="italic">S.I.I.,</hi> Vol. XIX No. 141.</p>						

						</summary>
